That's actually the missing piece. Once you understand these two concepts, the entire debugging process makes sense.

---

# First: What is a serverless function?

Think about a normal backend.

Normally you write:

```text
React Frontend
      │
      ▼
Express Server (always running)
      │
      ▼
Gemini API
```

Your Express server is **always alive**.

You run

```bash
npm start
```

and Node sits there waiting.

```
Request 1
     │
     ▼
Node handles it

Request 2
     │
     ▼
Node handles it

Request 3
     │
     ▼
Node handles it
```

It's like a receptionist sitting at a desk all day waiting for customers.

---

A **serverless function** works differently.

There is **no server waiting**.

Instead, Vercel says:

> "Oh, someone requested `/api/analyze`."

Then it does this:

```
Incoming Request
      │
      ▼
Start a fresh Node process
      │
      ▼
Run analyze.ts
      │
      ▼
Return response
      │
      ▼
Destroy the process
```

The process lives for maybe 1–5 seconds.

Then it disappears.

Every request starts from scratch.

That's why they're called **serverless**.

There *is* a server.

You just don't manage it.

Vercel creates it for one request.

---

# What is Node?

Node.js is simply JavaScript running outside the browser.

Normally JavaScript runs here:

```
Chrome
Firefox
Edge
```

Node lets JavaScript run here:

```
Linux Server
Windows
Mac
```

So when Vercel executes

```ts
api/analyze.ts
```

it is literally running

```
Node.js
```

on one of Vercel's machines.

---

# What is ESM?

This is the confusing part.

JavaScript has **two module systems**.

## Old one

```js
const express = require("express");

module.exports = app;
```

This is called **CommonJS**.

---

## New one

```js
import express from "express";

export default app;
```

This is called **ES Modules (ESM).**

Your project uses this because your package.json contains

```json
"type": "module"
```

That tells Node:

> "Treat every file as an ES Module."

---

# Why did ESM matter?

This is where the bug came from.

Imagine this folder:

```
constants/
      index.ts
```

You wrote

```ts
import { prepareInstructions } from "../constants";
```

Vite says

> "Oh, he means"

```
constants/index.ts
```

and happily loads it.

Node ESM says

> "No."

It looks for exactly

```
constants
```

It sees

```
constants/
```

which is a folder.

Node says

> "You imported a directory."

and throws

```
ERR_UNSUPPORTED_DIR_IMPORT
```

before it even runs your code.

---

# Why didn't Gemini even get called?

Imagine your file.

```ts
import { prepareInstructions } from "../constants";

export default async function handler(...) {
    console.log("API HIT");

    ...
}
```

Node executes files like this:

## Step 1

Resolve every import.

```
import ...
import ...
import ...
```

Only after **every import succeeds**

does it continue.

## Step 2

Create the function.

## Step 3

Wait for requests.

---

Your execution never reached Step 2.

It died here:

```
import { prepareInstructions } from "../constants";
                    ▲
                    │
              crash happens here
```

That's why Vercel showed

```
External APIs

No outgoing requests
```

Gemini never had a chance.

---

# Why did it work locally?

Because locally the execution looked like

```
React Router
        │
        ▼
Vite Dev Server
        │
        ▼
"Don't worry, I'll resolve
../constants to index.ts."
```

Vite is very smart.

It fixes lots of things for developers.

Production doesn't.

Production uses plain Node.

Node is much stricter.

---

# Think of Vite as a helpful translator

Suppose you say

> "Take me to John's house."

Vite says

> "I know which John you mean."

Node says

> "There are three Johns.
> Give me the exact address."

Your import was essentially saying

```
Go to constants
```

Vite translated that into

```
Go to constants/index.ts
```

Node refused.

---

# The mental model I use

Whenever I see

```
api/
```

inside a Vercel project, I immediately think

```
This file is NOT running inside React.

This file is running inside Node.
```

So I ask myself

> If I copied this file onto a Linux server and ran it with plain Node...

would it still work?

That's exactly the environment Vercel is giving you.

---

This distinction—**browser (Vite/React)** vs **server (Node/Vercel Functions)**—is one of the biggest conceptual jumps in modern full-stack development. Once it clicks, a lot of these "works locally but not on Vercel" issues become much easier to reason about.
